I've got to give a talk in two hours too, so I hope I have a voice.

00:11:10.140 --> 00:11:10.720
Speak quietly.

00:11:12.600 --> 00:11:14.120
Save a little bit for that.

00:11:17.700 --> 00:11:20.860
One of the questions you said was that people still just have

00:11:21.460 --> 00:11:22.760
core data science questions.

00:11:23.020 --> 00:11:29.680
They're not necessarily trying to figure out how LLMs are going to change the world, but how do you do that with pandas or whatever?

00:11:29.920 --> 00:11:31.460
What are your thoughts on this?

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:32.180
Yeah.

00:11:32.250 --> 00:11:32.660
What are your takeaways?

00:11:33.540 --> 00:11:35.660
So I alluded to the fact I have an academic background.

00:11:35.840 --> 00:11:41.160
I've probably talked about this on the last podcast, but basically my background is in behavioral sciences.

00:11:41.840 --> 00:11:47.040
So a lot of core statistics and working with what's called tabular data, data and tables.

00:11:49.600 --> 00:11:55.700
pretty much I would say look this is a guesstimate this is not scientific but my kind of gut feeling

00:11:56.740 --> 00:12:01.100
PyCon after PyCon of conference after conference that I do I think like 80 percent of people are

00:12:01.260 --> 00:12:06.280
probably still doing this stuff because business questions are not necessarily solved with the

00:12:06.380 --> 00:12:11.800
cutting edge business questions are solved with the simplest possible models that will address

00:12:12.040 --> 00:12:17.779
your needs I think we talked about this in the last podcast so like for an example my last job

00:12:18.100 --> 00:12:21.660
We had to deal with low latency systems, like very low latency.

00:12:22.460 --> 00:12:24.880
So we used DecisionTree to solve the problem.

00:12:25.180 --> 00:12:26.820
DecisionTree is a very old algorithm.

00:12:26.980 --> 00:12:30.380
It's not sexy anymore, but everyone's secretly still using it.

00:12:31.110 --> 00:12:34.560
And so, yeah, some people are doing cutting-edge LLM stuff.

00:12:35.100 --> 00:12:41.080
But my feeling is this is a technology that maybe has more interest

00:12:41.340 --> 00:12:45.959
than real profitable applications because these are expensive models

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:50.400
to run and deploy and to set up reliable pipelines for.

00:12:52.400 --> 00:12:56.860
Yeah, my gut feeling is a lot of people still just doing boring linear regression,

00:12:57.180 --> 00:12:58.980
which I will defend until the day I live.

00:12:59.350 --> 00:13:00.240
My favorite algorithm.

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:01.820
Amazing.

00:13:02.980 --> 00:13:05.540
Yeah, and I mean, I think we've seen that in our work as well,

00:13:05.780 --> 00:13:09.740
is we don't per se need the biggest, fanciest thing.

00:13:09.740 --> 00:13:14.180
We need something that works and provides users with useful information.

00:13:15.740 --> 00:13:22.540
I think there's also still a lot of problems with large language models, like Simon alluded to it in the keynote today around security.

00:13:23.720 --> 00:13:27.720
So if you want to put this into a product, it's still kind of early days.

00:13:29.040 --> 00:13:34.540
But I don't think those base kind of NLP techniques are going to go away anytime soon.

00:13:34.660 --> 00:13:39.380
And I think like we spoke about learners earlier and people coming into the field.

00:13:39.980 --> 00:13:46.040
there's still a huge amount of value just to go and learn this core aspects that will serve you

00:13:46.220 --> 00:13:52.780
really well. Absolutely. Way more than LLMs and AIs and all that stuff. You can use a LLM to learn it.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:58.420
You too, Chris? That's what we just saw in the keynote. Yeah, absolutely. And I also think

00:13:59.720 --> 00:14:04.400
what people are going to do with LLMs and stuff a lot is ask it to help keep me this little bit

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:08.100
of code or that bit of code. But you're going to need to be able to look at it and say, yeah,

00:14:08.180 --> 00:14:12.400
that does make sense. Yeah, that does fit in. And so you need to know that's a reasonable use of

00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:20.560
pandas. What do you think, Maria? I completely agree. The LLM school is kind of complex. I think

00:14:20.640 --> 00:14:25.880
it has a lot of potential. And I think that a lot of people could see this potential and everyone

00:14:26.020 --> 00:14:33.659
is getting very excited and even a bit in a hype because of that. However, has a lot of limitations

00:14:33.800 --> 00:14:42.520
still nowadays, I can tell you, because I am currently working with LLMs for solving the

00:14:42.860 --> 00:14:49.600
real world problems that we were mentioning about the sustainable packaging. And it's very

00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:54.760
challenging, to be honest. It's more challenging than people is mentioning. It's not only

00:14:54.940 --> 00:14:59.900
hallucinations. It's hallucination, of course, but also if you are doing fine-tuning models,

00:15:00.120 --> 00:15:05.220
also you're gonna later on need to think how you're gonna deploy that, how much

00:15:05.220 --> 00:15:11.820
gonna cost you the inference of that, how gonna cause in sense of electricity

00:15:12.320 --> 00:15:22.300
price, CO2, print and long etc. I think that we are in the process.

00:15:23.780 --> 00:15:25.980
I think we're at a very high hype cycle.

00:15:26.280 --> 00:15:43.980
I haven't seen anything like this since the dot-com days when pets.com was running around crazy and there was all sorts of bizarre Super Bowl ads just showing, you know, we have enough money to just burn it on silly things because we're a dot-com company.

00:15:45.160 --> 00:15:46.860
And I think we're kind of back there.

00:15:46.950 --> 00:15:54.120
But to me, the weird thing is it's not 100% reproducible, right?

00:15:55.040 --> 00:15:59.720
If you work with a lot of the data science tools, if you put in the same inputs, you get the same outputs.

00:16:00.500 --> 00:16:04.180
And here it's maybe. Has the context changed a little bit?

00:16:04.200 --> 00:16:07.020
Did they ask a little different question? Well, now you get a really different answer.

00:16:07.240 --> 00:16:11.700
It's like chaos theory for programming, but useful as well. It's odd.

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:17.980
Maybe a combination of different techniques is a path to what we call yours also, right?

00:16:18.100 --> 00:16:25.480
We can also combine the more classical NLP with the LLMs as an option or in other kind of modeling.

00:16:25.600 --> 00:16:29.820
It depends on what you try to solve, what is your business problem at the end.

00:16:30.280 --> 00:16:34.500
